refentry.refsect1:
&reftitle.description;
stringarraynullpreg_replace stringarraypattern stringarrayreplacement stringarraysubject intlimit-1 intcount&null;
Searches subject for matches to pattern and replaces them with replacement.
To match an exact string, rather than a pattern, consider using str_replace or str_ireplace instead of this function.

&reftitle.returnvalues;
preg_replace returns an array if the subject parameter is an array, or a string otherwise.
If matches are found, the new subject will be returned, otherwise subject will be returned unchanged or &null; if an error occurred.

&reftitle.errors;


 Using the "\e" modifier is an error;
 an E_WARNING is emitted in this case.

&pcre.pattern.warning;

  &reftitle.examples;



    Using backreferences followed by numeric literals


<?php
$string = 'April 15, 2003';
$pattern = '/(\w+) (\d+), (\d+)/i';
$replacement = '${1}1,$3';
echo preg_replace($pattern, $replacement, $string);
?>


    &example.outputs;


April1,2003







    Using indexed arrays with preg_replace


<?php
$string = 'The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.';
$patterns = array();
$patterns[0] = '/quick/';
$patterns[1] = '/brown/';
$patterns[2] = '/fox/';
$replacements = array();
$replacements[2] = 'bear';
$replacements[1] = 'black';
$replacements[0] = 'slow';
echo preg_replace($patterns, $replacements, $string);
?>


    &example.outputs;


The bear black slow jumps over the lazy dog.




     By ksorting patterns and replacements, we should get what we wanted.



<?php
ksort($patterns);
ksort($replacements);
echo preg_replace($patterns, $replacements, $string);
?>


    &example.outputs;


The slow black bear jumps over the lazy dog.







    Replacing several values


<?php
$patterns = array ('/(19|20)(\d{2})-(\d{1,2})-(\d{1,2})/',
                   '/^\s*{(\w+)}\s*=/');
$replace = array ('\3/\4/\1\2', '$\1 =');
echo preg_replace($patterns, $replace, '{startDate} = 1999-5-27');
?>


    &example.outputs;


$startDate = 5/27/1999







    Strip whitespace


     This example strips excess whitespace from a string.



<?php
$str = 'foo   o';
$str = preg_replace('/\s\s+/', ' ', $str);
// This will be 'foo o' now
echo $str;
?>







    Using the count parameter


<?php
$count = 0;

echo preg_replace(array('/\d/', '/\s/'), '*', 'xp 4 to', -1 , $count);
echo $count; //3
?>


    &example.outputs;


xp***to
3
